// Shared MMIO register addresses `use`d by both examples/common_stm32/
// eth.tkb and examples/common_stm32/sdmmc.tkb. Extracted here (GitHub
// issue #97 follow-up) after examples/http_server_sdcard/
// http_server_sdcard.tkb became the first program to need both HALs at
// once, exposing latent duplicate-global collisions (RCC_AHB1ENR/
// RCC_APB2ENR, and GPIOC_MODER/GPIOC_OSPEEDR -- both files independently
// configure GPIOC pins, eth.tkb for RMII, sdmmc.tkb for SDMMC1 D0..D3/CLK)
// that eth.tkb's and sdmmc.tkb's own independent declarations had never
// triggered before (the two files had never previously been compiled
// together). Same fix shape as examples/common_qemu/gic_regs.tkb's own
// split, for the same "one flat namespace" reason (see CLAUDE.md's issue
// #79 follow-up entry).
//
// Registers each file still declares on its own (not moved here) are the
// ones that do NOT collide: GPIOA/GPIOG (eth.tkb only), GPIOD/GPIOC_PUPDR
// (sdmmc.tkb only), and each file's own distinct GPIOC alternate-function
// register (GPIOC_AFRL vs. GPIOC_AFRH -- different bytes of the same
// 32-bit-pair AFR block, not actually the same address).
let RCC_AHB1ENR:   *io u32 = 0x40023830;
let RCC_APB2ENR:   *io u32 = 0x40023844;
let GPIOC_MODER:   *io u32 = 0x40020800;
let GPIOC_OSPEEDR: *io u32 = 0x40020808;
